# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: real-time-clock
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] A **backup battery** provides power to a system when the primary source of power is unavailable.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Backup batteries range from small single cells to retain clock time and date in computers, up to large battery room facilities that power uninterruptible power supply systems for large data centers.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Small backup batteries may be primary cells; rechargeable backup batteries are kept charged by the prime power supply.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Backup batteries in aircraft keep essential instruments and devices running in the event of an engine power failure.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Each aircraft has enough power in the backup batteries to facilitate a safe landing.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] The batteries keeping navigation, ELUs (emergency lighting units), emergency pressure or oxygen systems running at altitude, and radio equipment operational.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Larger aircraft have control surfaces that run on these backups as well.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Aircraft batteries are either nickel-cadmium or valve-regulated lead acid type.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] The battery keeps all necessary items running for between 30 minutes and 3 hours.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Large aircraft may have a ram air turbine to provide additional power during engine failures.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Backup batteries are almost always used in burglar alarms.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] The backup battery prevents the burglar from disabling the alarm by turning off power to the building.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Additionally these batteries power the remote cellular phone systems that thwart phone line snipping as well.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] The backup battery usually has a lifespan of 3-10 years depending on the make and model, and so if the battery runs flat, there is only one main source of power to the whole system which is the mains power.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Should this fail as well (for example, a power cut), it usually triggers a third backup battery located in the bellboxes on the outside of the building which simply triggers the bell or siren.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] This however means that the alarm cannot be stopped in any way apart from physically going outside to the bellbox and disabling the siren.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] It is also why if there is a power outage in the area, most burglar alarms do start ringing and cannot be realistically stopped until the main power is restored.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Modern personal computer motherboards have a backup battery to run the real-time clock circuit and retain configuration memory while the system is turned off.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] This is often called the CMOS battery or BIOS battery.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] The original IBM AT through to the PS/2 range, used a relatively large primary lithium battery, compared to later models, to retain the clock and configuration memory.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] These early machines required the backup battery to be replaced periodically due to the relatively large power consumption.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Some manufacturers of clone machines used a rechargeable battery to avoid the problems that could be created by a failing battery.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Modern systems use a coin style primary battery.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] In these later machines, the current draw is almost negligible and the primary batteries usually outlast the system that they support.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] It is rare to find rechargeable batteries in such systems.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Backup batteries are used in uninterruptible power supplies (UPS), and provide power to the computers they supply for a variable period after a power failure, usually long enough to at least allow the computer to be shut down gracefully.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] These batteries are often large valve regulated lead-acid batteries in smaller or portable systems.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Data center UPS backup batteries may be wet cell lead-acid or nickel cadmium batteries, with lithium ion cells available in some ratings.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Server-grade disk array controllers often contain onboard disk buffer, and provide an option for a "backup battery unit" (BBU) to maintain the contents of this cache after power loss.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] If this battery is present, disk writes can be considered completed when they reach the cache, thus speeding up I/O throughput by not waiting for the hard drive.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] This operation mode is called "write-back caching".
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] A local backup battery unit is necessary in some telephony and combined telephony/data applications built with use of digital passive optical networks.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] In such networks there are active units on telephone exchange side and on the user side, but nodes between them are all passive in the meaning of electrical power usage.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] So, if a building (such as an apartment house) loses power, the network continues to function.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] The user side must have standby power since operating power isn't transferred over data optical line.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] A valve-regulated lead-acid battery (VRLA) is a battery type that is popular in telecommunications network environments as a reliable backup power source.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] VRLA batteries are used in the outside plant at locations such as Controlled Environmental Vaults (CEVs), Electronic Equipment Enclosures (EEEs), and huts, and in uncontrolled structures such as cabinets.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] *VRLA Battery String Certification Levels Based on Requirements for Safety and Performance*, is a new industry-approved set of VRLA requirements that provides a three-level compliance system.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] The compliance system provides a common framework for evaluating and qualifying various valve-regulated lead-acid battery technologies.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] The framework intends to alleviate the complexities associated with product introduction and qualification.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] For a VRLA, the quality system employed by the manufacturer is an important key to the overall reliability of it.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Cartridge-based video games sometimes contain a battery which is used to preserve the contents of a small RAM chip on which saved games and/or high scores are recorded.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Power failure in a hospital would result in life-threatening conditions for patients.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Patients undergoing surgery or on life support are reliant on a consistent power supply.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Backup generators or batteries supply power to critical equipment until main power can be restored.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Power failure in a power station that produces electricity would result in a blackout situation that would cause irreparable damage to equipment such as the turbine-generator.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] The safety of power station employees is a major concern during an unscheduled power outage at a power plant.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] A bank of large station backup batteries are used to power uninterruptible power supplies as well as directly power emergency oil pumps for up to 8 hours while normal power is being restored to the power station.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Tesla, Inc installed the world's largest lithium ion battery pack for the government of South Australia in 2017; to help alleviate energy (electricity) blackouts in the state.
[src:real-time-clock/backup-battery] Tesla met the guarantee by Elon Musk of installation in 100 days or it would be free.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] A **real-time clock** (**RTC**) is an electronic timekeeping device, most often in the form of an integrated circuit (IC).
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Although the term often refers to the devices in personal computers, servers and embedded systems, RTCs are present in almost any electronic device that needs to keep accurate time of day.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] The term *real-time clock* is used to avoid confusion with ordinary hardware clocks, which are only signals that govern digital electronics, and do not count time in human units.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] RTC should not be confused with real-time computing, which shares its three-letter acronym but does not directly relate to time of day.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] A GPS receiver can shorten its startup time by comparing the current time, according to its RTC, with the time at which it last had a valid signal.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] If it has been less than a few hours, then the previous ephemeris is still usable.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Some motherboards are made without RTCs.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] The RTC may be omitted out of a desire to save money or reduce possible sources of hardware failure.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] RTCs often have an alternate source of power, so they can continue to keep time while the primary source of power is off or unavailable.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] This alternate source of power is normally a lithium battery in older systems, but some newer systems use a supercapacitor, because they are rechargeable and can be soldered.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] The alternate power source can also supply power to battery backed RAM.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Most RTCs use a crystal oscillator, but some have the option of using the power line frequency.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] The crystal frequency is usually 32.768 kHz, the same frequency used in quartz clocks and watches.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Being exactly 215 cycles per second, it is a convenient rate to use with simple binary counter circuits.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] The low frequency saves power, while remaining above human hearing range.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] The quartz tuning fork of these crystals does not change size much from temperature, so temperature does not change its frequency much.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Some RTCs use a micromechanical resonator on the silicon chip of the RTC.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] This reduces the size and cost of an RTC by reducing its parts count.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Micromechanical resonators are much more sensitive to temperature than quartz resonators.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] So, these compensate for temperature changes using an electronic thermometer and electronic logic.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Typical crystal RTC accuracy specifications are from ±100 to ±20 parts per million (8.6 to 1.7 seconds per day), but temperature-compensated RTC ICs are available accurate to less than 5 parts per million.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] In practical terms, this is good enough to perform celestial navigation, the classic task of a chronometer.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] In 2011, chip-scale atomic clocks became available.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Although vastly more expensive and power-hungry (120 mW vs. <1 μW), they keep time within 50 parts per trillion (5×10−11).
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Many integrated circuit manufacturers make RTCs, including Epson, Intersil, IDT, Maxim, NXP Semiconductors, Texas Instruments, STMicroelectronics and Ricoh.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] A common RTC used in single-board computers is the Maxim Integrated DS1307.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] The RTC was introduced to PC compatibles by the IBM PC/AT in 1984, which used a Motorola MC146818 RTC.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Later, Dallas Semiconductor made compatible RTCs, which were often used in older personal computers, and are easily found on motherboards because of their distinctive black battery cap and silkscreened logo.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] A standard CMOS interface is available for the PC RTC.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] In newer computer systems, the RTC is integrated into the southbridge chip.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Some microcontrollers have a real-time clock built in, generally only the ones with many other features and peripherals.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Some modern computers receive clock information by digital radio and use it to promote time standards.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] There are two common methods: Most cell phone protocols (e.g., LTE) directly provide the current local time.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] If an internet radio is available, a computer may use the network time protocol.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Computers used as local time servers occasionally use GPS or ultra-low frequency radio transmissions broadcast by a national standards organization (i.e. a radio clock).
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] The following system is well-known to embedded systems programmers, who sometimes must construct RTCs in systems that lack them.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Most computers have one or more hardware timers that use timing signals from quartz crystals or ceramic resonators.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] These have inaccurate absolute timing (more than 100 parts per million) that is yet very repeatable (often less than 1 ppm).
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Software can do the math to make these into accurate RTCs.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] The hardware timer can produce a periodic interrupt, e.g., 50 Hz, to mimic a historic RTC (see below).
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] When the *time* variable exceeds a constant, usually a power of two, the nominal, calculated clock time (say, for 1/50 of a second) is subtracted from *time*, and the clock's timing-chain software is invoked to count fractions of seconds, seconds, etc.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] With 32-bit variables for time and rate, the mathematical resolution of "rate" can exceed one part per billion.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] The clock remains accurate because it will occasionally skip a fraction of a second or increment by two fractions.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] The tiny skip (jitter) is imperceptible for almost all real uses of an RTC.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] The complexity with this system is determining the instantaneous corrected value for the variable *rate*.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] The simplest system tracks RTC time and reference time between two settings of the clock, and divides reference time by RTC time to find *rate*.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Internet time is often accurate to less than 20 milliseconds, so 8000 or more seconds (2.2 or more hours) of separation between settings can usually divide the forty milliseconds (or less) of error to less than 5 parts per million to get chronometer-like accuracy.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] The main complexity with this system is converting dates and times to counts of seconds, but methods are well known.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] If the RTC runs when a unit is off, usually the RTC will run at two rates, one when the unit is on and another when off.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] This is because the temperature and power-supply voltage in each state is consistent.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] To adjust for these states, the software calculates two rates.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] First, software records the RTC time, reference time, on seconds and off seconds for the two intervals between the last three times that the clock is set.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Using this, it can measure the accuracy of the two intervals, with each interval having a different distribution of on and off seconds.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] The rate math solves two linear equations to calculate two rates, one for on and the other for off.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Another approach measures the temperature of the oscillator with an electronic thermometer (e.g., a thermistor and analog-to-digital converter) and uses a polynomial to calculate *rate* about once per minute.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] These require a calibration that measures the frequency at several temperatures, and then a linear regression to find the equation of temperature.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] The most common quartz crystals in a system are SC-cut crystals, and their rates over temperature can be characterized with a 3rd-degree polynomial.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] So, to calibrate these, the frequency is measured at four temperatures.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] The common tuning-fork-style crystals used in watches and many RTC components have parabolic (2nd-degree) equations of temperature, and can be calibrated with only 3 measurements.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] MEMS oscillators vary, from 3rd degree to fifth degree polynomials, depending on their mechanical design, and so need from four to six calibration measurements.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Something like this approach might be used in commercial RTC ICs, but the actual methods of efficient high-speed manufacturing are proprietary.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Some computer designs such as the smaller IBM System/360, PDP-8 and Data General Nova used a real-time clock that was accurate, simple and low cost.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] In Europe, North America and some other grids, the frequency of the AC mains is adjusted to the long-term frequency accuracy of the national standards.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] In those grids, clocks using AC mains can keep perfect time without adjustment.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Such clocks are not practical in portable computers or grids (e.g., in South Asia) that do not regulate the frequency of AC mains.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] These computers' power supplies use a transformer or resistor divider to produce a sine wave at logic voltages.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] This signal is conditioned by a zero crossing detector, either using a linear amplifier or a schmitt trigger.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] The result is a square wave with single, fast edges at the mains frequency.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] This logic signal triggers an interrupt.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] The interrupt handler software usually counts cycles, seconds, etc.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] In this way, it can provide an entire clock and calendar.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] In the IBM 360, the interrupt updates a 64-bit count of microseconds utilized by standardized systems software.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] The clock's jitter error is half if the clock interrupts for each zero crossing, instead of each cycle.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] The clock also usually formed the basis of computers' software timing chains; e.g., it was usually the timer used to switch tasks in an operating system.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Counting timers used in modern computers provide similar features at lower precision, and may trace their requirements to this type of clock.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] A software-based clock must be set each time its computer is turned on.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] Originally, this was done by computer operators.
[src:real-time-clock/real-time-clock] When the Internet became commonplace, network time protocols were used to automatically set clocks of this type.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] A **time standard** is a specification for measuring time: either the rate at which time passes or points in time or both.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] In modern times, several time specifications have been officially recognized as standards, where formerly they were matters of custom and practice.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] An example of a kind of time standard can be a time scale, specifying a method for measuring divisions of time.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] A standard for civil time can specify both time intervals and time-of-day.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Standardized time measurements are made using a clock to count periods of some period changes, which may be either the changes of a natural phenomenon or of an artificial machine.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Historically, time standards were often based on the Earth's rotational period.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] From the late 18 century to the 19th century it was assumed that the Earth's daily rotational rate was constant.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Astronomical observations of several kinds, including eclipse records, studied in the 19th century, raised suspicions that the rate at which Earth rotates is gradually slowing and also shows small-scale irregularities, and this was confirmed in the early twentieth century.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Time standards based on Earth rotation were replaced (or initially supplemented) for astronomical use from 1952 onwards by an *ephemeris time* standard based on the Earth's orbital period and in practice on the motion of the Moon.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] The invention in 1955 of the caesium atomic clock has led to the replacement of older and purely astronomical time standards, for most practical purposes, by newer time standards based wholly or partly on atomic time.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Various types of second and day are used as the basic time interval for most time scales.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Other intervals of time (minutes, hours, and years) are usually defined in terms of these two.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] There have only ever been three definitions of the second: as a fraction of the day, as a fraction of an extrapolated year, and as the microwave frequency of a caesium atomic clock.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] In early history, clocks were not accurate enough to track seconds.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] After the invention of mechanical clocks, the CGS system and MKS system of units both defined the second as 1⁄86,400 of a mean solar day.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] MKS was adopted internationally during the 1940s.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] In the late 1940s, quartz crystal oscillator clocks could measure time more accurately than the rotation of the Earth.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Metrologists also knew that Earth's orbit around the Sun (a year) was much more stable than Earth's rotation.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] This led to the definition of ephemeris time and the tropical year, and the ephemeris second was defined as "the fraction 1⁄31,556,925.9747 of the tropical year for 1900 January 0 at 12 hours ephemeris time".
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] This definition was adopted as part of the International System of Units in 1960.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Most recently, atomic clocks have been developed that offer improved accuracy.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Since 1967, the SI base unit for time is the SI second, defined as exactly "the duration of 9,192,631,770 periods of the radiation corresponding to the transition between the two hyperfine levels of the ground state of the caesium-133 atom" (at a temperature of 0 K and at mean sea level).
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] The SI second is the basis of all atomic timescales, e.g. coordinated universal time, GPS time, International Atomic Time, etc.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Geocentric Coordinate Time (TCG) is a coordinate time having its spatial origin at the center of Earth's mass.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] TCG is a theoretical ideal, and any particular realization will have measurement error.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] International Atomic Time (TAI) is the primary physically realized time standard.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] TAI is produced by the International Bureau of Weights and Measures (BIPM), and is based on the combined input of many atomic clocks around the world, each corrected for environmental and relativistic effects (both gravitational and because of speed, like in GNSS).
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] TAI is not related to TCG directly but rather is a realization of Terrestrial Time (TT), a theoretical timescale that is a rescaling of TCG such that the time rate approximately matches proper time at mean sea level.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Universal Time (UT1) is the Earth Rotation Angle (ERA) linearly scaled to match historical definitions of mean solar time at 0° longitude.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] At high precision, Earth's rotation is irregular and is determined from the positions of distant quasars using long baseline interferometry, laser ranging of the Moon and artificial satellites, as well as GPS satellite orbits.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) is an atomic time scale designed to approximate UT1.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] UTC differs from TAI by an integral number of seconds.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] UTC is kept within 0.9 second of UT1 by the introduction of one-second steps to UTC, the "leap second".
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] To date these steps (and difference "TAI-UTC") have always been positive.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] The Global Positioning System broadcasts a very precise time signal worldwide, along with instructions for converting GPS time (GPST) to UTC.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] It was defined with a constant offset from TAI: GPST = TAI - 19 s.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] The GPS time standard is maintained independently but regularly synchronized with or from, UTC time.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Standard time or civil time in a time zone deviates a fixed, round amount, usually a whole number of hours, from some form of Universal Time, usually UTC.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] The offset is chosen such that a new day starts approximately while the Sun is crossing the nadir meridian.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Alternatively the difference is not really fixed, but it changes twice a year by a round amount, usually one hour, see Daylight saving time.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Julian day number is a count of days elapsed since Greenwich mean noon on 1 January 4713 B.C., Julian proleptic calendar.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] The Julian Date is the Julian day number followed by the fraction of the day elapsed since the preceding noon.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Conveniently for astronomers, this avoids the date skip during an observation night.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Modified Julian day (MJD) is defined as MJD = JD - 2400000.5.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] An MJD day thus begins at midnight, civil date.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Julian dates can be expressed in UT1, TAI, TT, etc. and so for precise applications the timescale should be specified, e.g.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Barycentric Coordinate Time (TCB) is a coordinate time having its spatial origin at the center of mass of the Solar System, which is called the barycenter.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Conversions between atomic time systems (TAI, GPST, and UTC) are for the most part exact.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] However, GPS time is a measured value as opposed to a computed "paper" scale.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] As such it may differ from UTC(USNO) by a few hundred nanoseconds, which in turn may differ from official UTC by as much as 26 nanoseconds.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Conversions for UT1 and TT rely on published difference tables which as of 2022 are specified to 10 microseconds and 0.1 nanoseconds respectively.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] DUT1 = UT1 − UTC published in IERS Bulletins or U.S.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] DTT = TT − TAI − 32.184 s published in BIPM's TT(BIPM) tables.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] TCB is a linear transformation of TDB and TDB differs from TT in small, mostly periodic terms.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Neglecting these terms (on the order of 2 milliseconds for several millennia around the present epoch), TCB is related to TT by: TCB − TT = *LB* × (JD − 2443144.5) × 86400 seconds.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] The scale difference *LB* has been defined by the IAU to be 1.550519768e-08 exactly.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Apparent solar time or true solar time is based on the solar day, which is the period between one solar noon (passage of the real Sun across the meridian) and the next.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] A solar day is approximately 24 hours of mean time.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Because the Earth's orbit around the Sun is elliptical, and because of the obliquity of the Earth's axis relative to the plane of the orbit (the ecliptic), the apparent solar day varies a few dozen seconds above or below the mean value of 24 hours.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] As the variation accumulates over a few weeks, there are differences as large as 16 minutes between apparent solar time and mean solar time (see Equation of time).
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] However, these variations cancel out over a year.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] There are also other perturbations such as Earth's wobble, but these are less than a second per year.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] A sidereal rotation is the time it takes the Earth to make one revolution with rotation to the stars, approximately 23 hours 56 minutes 4 seconds.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] A mean solar day is about 3 minutes 56 seconds longer than a mean sidereal day, or 1⁄366 more than a mean sidereal day.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] In astronomy, sidereal time is used to predict when a star will reach its highest point in the sky.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] It is well known that observations of the Sun pose substantial obstacles to the achievement of accuracy in measurement.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] It has been superseded by Universal Time.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Greenwich Mean Time was originally mean time deduced from meridian observations made at the Royal Greenwich Observatory (RGO).
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] The principal meridian of that observatory was chosen in 1884 by the International Meridian Conference to be the Prime Meridian.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] UT1 is still in reality mean time at Greenwich.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Today, GMT is a time zone but is still the legal time in the UK in winter (and as adjusted by one hour for summer time).
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] But Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) (an atomic-based time scale which is always kept within 0.9 second of UT1) is in common actual use in the UK, and the name GMT is often used to refer to it.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Versions of Universal Time such as UT0 and UT2 have been defined but are no longer in use.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Ephemeris time (ET) and its successor time scales described below have all been intended for astronomical use, e.g. in planetary motion calculations, with aims including uniformity, in particular, freedom from irregularities of Earth rotation.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Some of these standards are examples of dynamical time scales and/or of coordinate time scales.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Ephemeris Time was from 1952 to 1976 an official time scale standard of the International Astronomical Union; it was a dynamical time scale based on the orbital motion of the Earth around the Sun, from which the ephemeris second was derived as a defined fraction of the tropical year.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] This ephemeris second was the standard for the SI second from 1956 to 1967, and it was also the source for calibration of the caesium atomic clock; its length has been closely duplicated, to within 1 part in 1010, in the size of the current SI second referred to atomic time.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] This Ephemeris Time standard was non-relativistic and did not fulfil growing needs for relativistic coordinate time scales.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] It was in use for the official almanacs and planetary ephemerides from 1960 to 1983, and was replaced in official almanacs for 1984 and after, by numerically integrated Jet Propulsion Laboratory Development Ephemeris DE200 (based on the JPL relativistic coordinate time scale Teph).
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] For applications at the Earth's surface, ET's official replacement was Terrestrial Dynamical Time (TDT), which maintained continuity with it.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] TDT is a uniform atomic time scale, whose unit is the SI second.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] TDT is tied in its rate to the SI second, as is International Atomic Time (TAI), but because TAI was somewhat arbitrarily defined at its inception in 1958 to be initially equal to a refined version of UT, TDT was offset from TAI, by a constant 32.184 seconds.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] The offset provided a continuity from Ephemeris Time to TDT.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] TDT has since been redefined as Terrestrial Time (TT).
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] For the calculation of ephemerides, Barycentric Dynamical Time (TDB) was officially recommended to replace ET.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] TDB is similar to TDT but includes relativistic corrections that move the origin to the barycenter, hence it is a dynamical time at the barycenter.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] TDB differs from TT only in periodic terms.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] The difference is at most 2 milliseconds.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] Deficiencies were found in the definition of TDB (though not affecting Teph), and TDB has been replaced by Barycentric Coordinate Time (TCB) and Geocentric Coordinate Time (TCG), and redefined to be JPL ephemeris time argument Teph, a specific fixed linear transformation of TCB.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] As defined, TCB (as observed from the Earth's surface) is of divergent rate relative to all of ET, Teph and TDT/TT; and the same is true, to a lesser extent, of TCG.
[src:real-time-clock/time-standard] The ephemerides of Sun, Moon and planets in current widespread and official use continue to be those calculated at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory (updated as from 2003 to DE405) using as argument Teph.
